'''Radio Polynesia''' is a major [[radio station]] and source of [[news]] and [[information]] in [[Samoa]]. Founded in 1989, the radio station's head office is situated in Savalalo, in the capital [[Apia]].<ref name=so>{{cite news |first=Muavae |last=Faletoi |title=Radio Polynesia 20th birthday celebration cancelled |url=http://www.samoaobserver.ws/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=13710:radio-polynesia&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=50 |work=[[Samoa Observer]] |publisher= |date=2009-10-01 |accessdate=2009-10-01}}</ref> Radio Polynesia operates four separate radio stations, broadcasting in both [[English language|English]] and [[Samoan language|Samoan]]. In 1998, the station launched Talofa FM, broadcast only in the Samoan language with 100% national coverage including the outer island of [[Savai'i]].
Radio Polynesia is owned by promoter and businessman [[Maposua Rudolf Keil]],<ref>IFEX [http://www.ifex.org/samoa/1997/11/18/samoan_government_discusses_closing Samoan government discusses closing down independent radio station]</ref> who also owns the local Majik Cinema in Apia.<ref>Nine MSN [http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=102603 Samoa bans Da Vinci Code film] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120929211734/http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=102603 |date=2012-09-29 }}</ref> The radio station is managed by his son Corey Keil.<ref>Radio Heritage Foundation [http://www.radioheritage.net/FDD3.asp More Pacific Radio Heritage Documentaries]</ref> [[Olga Keil]] is a journalist based with the station.<ref>BBC News http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/8282115.stm Eyewitness: Pacific tsunami, OLGA KEIL, a journalist based with Radio Polynesia in Western Samoa</ref>
A celebration marking of the 20th [[anniversary]] of Radio Polynesia was originally scheduled to take place on Tuesday, September 29, 2009.<ref name=so/> However, the celebration was cancelled due to the [[2009 Samoa earthquake and tsunami]], which devatstated the country the same day.<ref name=so/>
